ampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","Kent, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Andover, Hampshire, , England":"Andover, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1380–1407":"1380–1407","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1369–1435":"1369–1435","1403–1442":"1403–1442","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1405–Male":"1405–Deceased","1352–1407":"1352–1407","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1352":"1352","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1369":"1369","1401":"1401","about 1405":"about 1405","1442":"1442","1407":"1407","before 1380":"before 1380","1405":"1405","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","Kent, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Andover, Hampshire, , England":"Andover, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Warrener","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>warrennier</i> ‘warrener’, an officer employed to watch over game in a park or game preserve. Compare   Warren  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Warren","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Warin</i>, <i>Werin</i>, a borrowing of ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. Compare   Waring  .","English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from La Varrenne in Seine-Maritime, France, named with a Gaulish element probably descriptive of alluvial land or sandy soil. This was the name of a major Norman family after the Conquest. In Ireland, this name has been Gaelicized as <b>Bharain</b>.","Irish: adopted as an English form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b> (see   Murnane  ,   Warner  )."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Warrener was born in 1380, in Basingstoke, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Warrener, was 28 and her mother, Joan Carpenter, was 21. She married Walter Sandes in 1401, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1407, in Andover, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1380–1407":"1380–1407","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1369–1435":"1369–1435","1403–1442":"1403–1442","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1405–Male":"1405–Surnud","1352–1407":"1352–1407","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1352":"1352","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1369":"1369","1401":"1401","about 1405":"umbes 1405","1442":"1442","1407":"1407","before 1380":"enne 1380","1405":"1405","Basingstoke, Hampshire, England":"Basingstoke, Hampshire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","England":"England","Kent, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Andover, Hampshire, , England":"Andover, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–1407":"1380–1407","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1369–1435":"1369–1435","1403–1442":"14